segments.text: smaller towns to be from farming or ranching families, some wealthy, some not.
And so there was, so that dichotomy was there too, I think.
Were y'all, you were proud to be a part of the transition.
Did you hear anybody complaining about A&M going to the dogs or this being, did most people think this was progress, these changes?
Most people did.
However, we would talk of an old ag someplace who just thought that the presence of women on campus had just made everything go to hell.
We knew there were those voices out there.
We didn't pay much attention to them.
And y'all learned Aggie jokes.
Oh, yes.
All that.
Oh, yeah.
And how soon did you and your transition friends, meaning part of a transition, how soon before you all felt Aggie pride?
First day we were there.
Did you ever think about transferring?
Not for a heartbeat.
I couldn't imagine if gone.
That never crossed my mind.
What about the people around you in the dorms?
They were there.
They were committed.
They were there for the duration.
And there was a good survival rate academically?
Yes.
Yes.
As far as you knew, were the admission requirements about in order then?
Were they about appropriate for A&M standards?
I think so.
If you...
Anybody that really wanted to go there pretty much got in, I think, from...
that was not selective at all.
Trivia for you.
Before the Aspirations Report, one of the things we recommended was to start moving the admission requirements up.
The official admission requirements until 1963 or 4
other than being white and male, you had to have a diploma.
Nothing about grades, courses, class rank, scores or anything.
No felony convictions and no communicable diseases.
That's all it was.
So, obviously, we had a high flunk rate because there were people that couldn't make it.
And what I want to ask all the experts today who say, we need to do this, that, okay, how many people
can this institution best serve?
What should be the appropriate number?
We've got far, far, far more than that applying.
Yes.
Then on what basis do we select who gets to be here?
When I ran into that in Missouri and I had our registrar, I said, have the machine print out for us
What did a student need here in combination of high school record and test score, ACT and SAT, to have a high likelihood of a two-point at the end of the first?
And what we found, top quarter of both all the test scores and high school, if you're not in the top quarter of both, only on probation,
unless you went to one of the very, very, very, very, very selective prep schools in Kansas City or St. Louis.
Like if we were in the second quarter, Kincaid.
Yes, yes.
That makes a big difference.
Yeah, or Country Day or a place like that.
And that's a tough one, a tough one for this here.
What were the attitudes about the point of view, the philosophy of these students, your colleagues and their families?
What, liberal, conservative?
I would say fairly conservative.
I remember the Carter Ford election.
happened when I was on campus.
And if there was anybody on campus that supported Jimmy Carter, I don't remember who it was.
I remember everybody was in favor of Ford, whether you were a Republican or not.
So it was pretty conservative, no anti-war sentiment, patriotic, ambitious.
Kids wanted to go to graduate school, kids wanted to go to professional school.
The women of my core group of kids
four or five women that I've remained close to.
I'm a physician.
One's an attorney.
One is a retailer in New York City.
One is a high school teacher.
One is an entrepreneur.
None of us had kids right out of college.
Only one married right out of college.
We definitely were not there for our MRS degrees.
And, you know, have really all been very successful.
A couple of the women never had kids.
So it was...
Were there any majors that you and your closest friends kind of looked down on?
Yeah, the wildlife fisheries majors, some of the ag majors.
were like, well, okay, yeah.
Do your thing and that's fine, but.
In the term, in the meaning of the term diversity as we now use it, how diverse was the student body then?
It wasn't diverse at all.
The, you know, there were white students and black athletes.
You know, Fred McClure was a real.
What about Hispanic?
Hardly any.
International students?
A few, but they were mostly graduate students.
Jewish?
Not many.
But those that were here, did anybody think less of them?
I don't think so.
Religion was not a big issue at that point in time.
Were there religious activities that you and your friends participated in?
Not really.
I went to church a couple of times.
And this is from someone who had been to church every Sunday and very active in church youth activities, but I just didn't have room for that when I was at school.
I know there was a Catholic student union.
I think there was a Methodist, a Baptist student fellowship.
But they were not real active and real big at that point in time.
I know of no denomination nationally.
We're Presbyterian.
I know of no denomination nationally
And I don't know any institution nationally that is doing religious activities for undergraduates well.
Yeah, TCU doesn't.
No, no, no.
TCU, we have a real hard time with that.
And we're right across the street from campus and have a formal affiliation, and we still don't do it well.
I know, but there are probably more Baptist students at TCU than the same.
Probably.
I know at Austin College, Presbyterians are third in the number.
Now, there were no international...
events that stirred you and your, no Pearl Harbors, no D-days, nothing like this.
Mm-mm, mm-mm.
Nothing that caused you to lie awake at night?
Well, it was Watergate, and it was Nixon's resignation.
But we seemed so distant from that, because nobody had TVs in their rooms, and if you wanted to watch TV, you watched in one of the TV rooms down in the Commons.
And they tended to be crowded, and they were dark, and...
I didn't spend a lot of time in the TV rooms.
We got our news from The Bat.
What did y'all think of The Bat?
The Bat, everybody read it, but we thought that they were a bunch of wild-eyed liberal media freaks, and they had long hair, and they were kind of the hippies on campus.
They raised the GPA for transferring into journalism two weeks ago, they raised it to 2.2.

But I remember that was the first time I ever used a word processor, was when I ran for vice president for student services the spring of my sophomore year, or rules and regulations, vice president for rules and regulations for student government.
I got a vote of no confidence from the bat.
I didn't have anybody running against me, but I got a vote of no confidence just because I...
I'd been a secretary and stuff like that, and they really didn't know who I was.
I remember how mad I was.
There was a guy, Scott Sherman, I can't remember what his name was, who was a reporter for The Bat, but I also knew from student government, and I wanted to write a rebuttal.
He says, we'll print that, sure.
He says, really, it would be easiest if you just came down to wherever they wrote The Bat and
and just go ahead and type it in yourself.
And I typed a mile a minute.
So I went and he taught me how to use a word processor to write my rebuttal, which they did print, and I won the election.
Were you and your friends aware of any secret fraternities?
No, not at all.
You never heard of them?
Mm-mm, mm-mm.
official sororities and fraternities came to campus the year I was a freshman.
What did y'all think of that idea?
Horrible.
We thought it was just a disgrace to the A&M tradition.

And I can remember, because a bunch of my friends who had gone to other schools, TCU, were all Chi Omegas, and I remember I got a call from someone asking me if I would be one of the charter members of the Chi Omega chapter on campus.
And I thought, well, why in the hell would I want to do something stupid like that?
It really didn't want any part of it.
And the men and the women that were in sororities and fraternities, there were very few of them.
Invariably, they were big city, big high school, upper middle class kinds of kids, and they were pariahs.
They really were.
Did you know we now have a higher percentage per capita of fraternity and sorority members than UT does?
Yes.
Isn't that fascinating?
Last year, three of the core Yale leaders, in other words, there were core members and Yale leaders, were in fraternities.
Yeah.
I remember telling somebody the other day that there were guys in the core in fraternities, and they just blew them away.
I didn't realize any Yale leaders had been, but secret societies, no.
Apparently, they still exist.
TTs, True Texans, and then this one will stun you.
It goes back to the teens.
Sterling Evans was a member.
The Stickers, full name Schwa Stickers.
long before the Nazi Party discovered the Navajo and Hindu, I didn't know, both in India and in the United States for the, that was a good luck symbol.
And it was a welcoming symbol.
And apparently the purpose of both groups is very simple, to get their members elected to the key positions, used to be core commanders.
Who were the most, what were the most respected student leadership positions?
Corps commander, president of the student body.
Which of those would have had the highest?
Corps commander.
Really?
Okay.
Yeah, even then.
Yeah.
What about MSC council chairman or president?
Not nearly as high.
Okay.
Not nearly as high.
What about band commander?
Up there, but not at the top.
Did you all respect the band?
Oh, yes.
You didn't make fun of them?
Oh, sure we did.
Oh, okay.
Yeah, they were BQs.
But it was a good nature?
It was a good nature.
We really admired them, but we loved to give them a hard time for being kind of nerdy.
If a girl had a choice between a guy who was in the corps or not, was there any status difference?
A little bit.
You know, we...
The women like us that were boot chasers got teased and made fun of, but there was some status to going out with, especially an upperclassman in the Corps.
And did your co-eds use Aggie slang?
like boot chasers.
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Did you all adopt any of the food lingo from the dining hall?
Some of it.
Not the more descriptive terms, but... Did you ever at home get in trouble for slipping and using an Aggie slang term at home?
I never got in trouble, but probably the first time I, you know, piss hit or court hurt or something like that, I...
I was like, what did you just say?
Because, you know, being TCU people, they really weren't familiar with any of that.
And I kind of explained to them, that's what they're called.
They were like, well, okay, we can live with that.
It's getting close to 15 minutes.
Yeah, a few more minutes.
Yeah, let's keep talking.
Oh, okay.
And you don't remember ever hearing any real anti-female put-downs.
Women were welcome.
A few.

You know, there were probably some upperclassmen perhaps in the Corps that were so diehard old army kind of guys that, but, you know, I think most of the men appreciated having some women on campus finally.
Where did a, where did a co-ed turn for special advice?
To her friends.
Because there wasn't a dean of women.
Were you acquainted with John Coldis?
Yes.
What did you all think of him?
Oh, we adored him.
We just worshipped the ground he walked on.
One of the best there ever was.
And he would, and I didn't realize it until he told me last weekend when I saw him at John David Crowe's retirement party.
that he'd really only been there a year before I came.
And, but he was the most nurturing, supportive man.
We all just adored him.
You know, and if you got the, he had these Tuesday night dinners in the MSC where he would have some student leaders come.
If you got to do that, you were just, that was one of the most prestigious things on campus that you got to do.
I was on the search committee and I was stunned that we were considering a guy from East Texas.
No, he nationally.
And then another one that nationally is among the best there ever was is Bob Walker.
Yeah.
See, Bob has turned down the same job at Michigan.
Really?
And at Berkeley.
Those aren't good time ones.
See, those are really, really tough.
I remember Bob from when I was a freshman because he was very, you know, he was a wonderful mentor.
They kind of adopted all the president's scholars because there really weren't that many of us back then.
And I remember him from day one just being so supportive.
But Coldus was just such a sweetheart.
I remember when I was in medical school,
coming back to take my national boards in between second and third year, I house sat for them.
They let me stay in their house.
They were out of town, and so I got to stay there when I took my boards.
You know, just things like that that make so much difference in a student's life.
See, as a sideline watcher, I worry.
He and Ray Bowen are classmates.
And with Ray retiring,
I don't think Bob plans to ever retire.
I hope not.
Because he's so good.
Well, I hope not.
Gee, who is there?
Jack Kenny Williams.
Describe him as you students thought of him.
Everybody liked him.
He was popular.
He always had that smile on his face.
As women, we felt that he bridged the old A&M, new A&M thing well.
And I personally felt like he walked that tightrope pretty well.
I remember
He was not...
I don't remember being real close to students like Coldis or Stark or somebody like that, but everybody was very fond of him.
He was a very popular president.
But I do remember when we did Godspell that spring, we did it in the theater.
We didn't do it in the auditorium.
And he was there, front and center, for one of the first performances.
And I remember there was one scene where...
the kids go out in the audience and talk to the cast members during a song, and one of the more voluptuous women went and sat in his lap and sang to him, and he just got the biggest kick out of it.
And I remember how delighted we all were that he was such a good sport about it.
So many students nicknamed him Smiling Jack.
Oh, yeah, Smiling Jack.
And I know from these interviews that the board, then board of directors, they weren't regents yet,
guess how they knew to go look for him?
Because Earl Rutter told Ford All Britain and John Lindsay, they were flying Chicago in 1968.
My source of this is Ford.
And he said, I looked at Mr. Rutter and said, Earl, you really got A&M moving now.
God help us if it were to happen.
But if something happened to you, do you have somebody
He said, Rudder put his glass down and said, no, I don't.
And I learned in Europe that the CO may go down in battle.
And I got to do that.
Albritton said, we stopped it.
Then that night at supper, brought it back up.
And he said, Mr. Rutter said, I've been thinking about it since you asked me.

If something were ever to happen to me, you go to the University of Tennessee system, get their number two man, name is Jack Kenny Williams, first commissioner of higher education in Texas, organize the coordinating board.
But before he came to Texas, where he was highly regarded,

He started off teaching southern history, as I did, at a separate land grant school in a southern state which was all male, compulsory military, racially segregated, had a corps of cadets, and they made the changes at Clemson so that he would understand A&M well.
And he said then when Earl died,
Ford said, I was a new board member.
All I had to do was tell my colleagues, this is what.
This is what he wanted, yeah.
And so he said, we went and hired him on the spot.
Wow.
No presidential search, no search firm, no committee, no.
Have you all selected a firm yet, a search firm?
I don't know if the committee has selected a firm yet or not.
Not that I've heard of.
Bill Funk in Dallas is the best there is.
Well, we worked with him with the chancellor search.
I've known him for a little more than 15 years and he's good.
Yeah, I was impressed when I spoke with him because they were in the middle of that when I first came on the board and Bill kind of helped me get up to speed with the chancellor search.
Back to Williams, were you as a student aware of his heart attack?
of his illness in 76?
Yeah, yeah.
It was downplayed, but everybody realized that something had happened.
And see, the campus physician, whose name neither of us can remember for certain, is the one who saved his life at the house.
So the helicopter could take him to Houston.
And then DeBakey did some marvelous things.
But when Williams died, I think he was 68.
three or four, the oldest surviving male in the family tree history.
All William's males die.
Let's quit there.
Okay.
Let's quit there.
